    toModel (bt : BuildTree pos) : (Σ W : Finset (Finset Formula), KripkeModel W) :=
      ⟨ ((bt.allPreStates).map (List.toFinset ∘ PreState.forms)).toFinset -- W
      , { val := fun X p => Formula.atom_prop p ∈ X.1 -- valuation V(p)
        , Rel := fun a X Y => -- relation Rₐ
            ∃ φ, (~⌈·a⌉φ) ∈ X.1 ∧ (projection a X.1.toList).toFinset ∪ {~φ} ⊆ Y.1 }⟩
```

The definition of `WS` is the first component of `toModel bt`, so `WS = ((bt.allPreStates).map (List.toFinset ∘ PreState.forms)).toFinset`.

For `?d`, we need to show that for any `w ∈ WS`, any `α`, and any `φ ∈ w`, then `φ ∈ projection α w`.
The definition of `projection α w` is `List.toFinset (PreState.forms w ++ (if α.isAtomic then [Formula.neg (Formula.boxes α φ)] else []))`.

So, the goal is to show that for any `w ∈ WS`, `α`, and `φ ∈ w`, then `φ` is in the list `(PreState.forms w ++ (if α.isAtomic then [Formula.neg (Formula.boxes α φ)] else []))`.

Since `φ ∈ w`, and `w` is in `WS`, `w` is a `Finset Formula` that is the image of some `PreState bt π` under `PreState.forms`.
Specifically, `w` is constructed from `PreState.forms π` for some `π`.

So, we need to show that `φ` is in `PreState.forms π`.
But `φ ∈ w` means `φ ∈ ((bt.allPreStates).map (List.toFinset ∘ PreState.forms)).toFinset`.
This means `φ` is in the image of `List.toFinset ∘ PreState.forms` applied to `bt.allPreStates`.
So, there exists some `π ∈ bt.allPreStates` such that `φ ∈ (List.toFinset (PreState.forms π))`.

Therefore, `φ ∈ PreState.forms π`.
Since `φ` is in the list `PreState.forms π`, it is in the list `PreState.forms π ++ (if α.isAtomic then [Formula.neg (Formula.boxes α φ)] else [])`.
Therefore, `φ` is in the projection.

This reasoning can be formalized in Lean.

We will construct the proof for case `d`.

